  "text": "Hillslopes in the region show widespread evidence for gullying and mass movements (Figures 3 and S3) . As a result, we can examine the cosmogenic nuclide data from modern samples to gauge if our samples are sensitive to mass movements. Erosion rates from the tributary sand samples mostly fall between 0.02 and 0.1 mm yr À1 (Figure 7b ). This range broadly overlaps with the erosion rates measured on sand samples from the Río Grande, whose large drainage area (~3700 km 2 ) should make the samples relatively insensitive to landslides [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , and it overlaps with rates from the convex bedrock ridges, which appear to be unaffected by sudden mass wasting processes. Based on the overlapping rates, we infer that the sand samples from the tributaries are also minimally affected by landslides. One exception is the",
